					<h4>
						The idea
					</h4>
					<p>The simplest way to describe "Fork my religion" is that it is a collaborative way of figuring out what beliefs and values are important.
I presented the project in a humourous way at Tech Crunch but I actually believe it can serve a very important goal.  Issues such as when it is acceptable to tell a lie or to commit suicide are incredibly important and most people have an opinion about this.  The problem is that few people have arrived at their opinion through critical thinking.  "Fork my religion" will allow you to browse different opinions and see which you like best.
The key part is that if you see something you like, you can improve it by "forking it".  This is a concept from the geeky programming world where you are able to create your own version of someone elses code and improve it without interfering with the original.  As different versions emerge, the best ones can be reincorporated into the original.  The high quality of open source software out there proves that this system of collaboration works very well</p>
